{"key":"post-15401801","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15401801</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Can spent substrate be used as spawn?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Could I take the substrate that I had just harvested my 2nd or 3rd flush from and layer/mix it in a monotub?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not only is it 'spent', meaning the mycelium has slowed down or nearly stopped after producing fruits, a previously flushed substrate will have had billions of mold spores land on it.&amp;nbsp; If you use this as spawn, you place those mold spores into fresh substrate, where they will germinate and grow much faster than the leftover mushroom mycelium, ruining your grow.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One use for spent substrates is to place into a manure mix in your garden area, where they may or may not fruit again, but regardless, the fungi is beneficial to your plants.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15401803</next>\n<prev>15401770</prev>\n<first>15400219</first>\n<last>15401803</last>\n<when>1321887774</when>\n<utime>11/21/11 05:02 PM</utime>\n</post>"}